### Custom Hooks

Custom hooks let you extract component logic into reusable functions. They are JavaScript functions that can call other hooks and share stateful logic across components.

---

### Naming Convention

Custom hooks must start with `use` followed by a capital letter (e.g., `useFetch`, `useLocalStorage`).

### Basic Custom Hook

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function useWindowWidth() {
  const [width, setWidth] = useState(window.innerWidth);

  useEffect(() => {
    const handleResize = () => setWidth(window.innerWidth);
    window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
    return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  }, []);

  return width;
}
```

### Using the Hook

```jsx
function MyComponent() {
  const width = useWindowWidth();
  return <p>Window width: {width}px</p>;
}
```

### Common Custom Hook Patterns

| Hook | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `useFetch(url)` | Data fetching with loading/error |
| `useLocalStorage(key)` | Synced localStorage state |
| `useDebounce(value, delay)` | Debounced value |
| `useToggle(initial)` | Boolean toggle |
| `useMediaQuery(query)` | Responsive breakpoints |

### Example: useFetch

```jsx
function useFetch(url) {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    setLoading(true);
    fetch(url)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        setData(data);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, [url]);

  return { data, loading };
}
```

> **Key Point:** Custom hooks promote code reuse and separation of concerns. They can call other hooks, manage state, and return any value. Two components using the same custom hook share logic but not state.

